<p style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.85em;color:#888">Updated July 2026 &middot; Hub page</p>
<h1>The ICU Emergencies Library &mdash; Every Guide, Organized by System</h1>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">This library grew one emergency at a time, and it is now large enough that the hardest part is finding the guide you need at 3 a.m. This hub organizes every ICU emergency guide on the site by body system and by the kind of trouble you are looking at. Each guide is written the same way: what the emergency actually is physiologically, what the nurse sees first, what the treatment sequence is and why the order matters, and the specific traps that hurt patients.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>How to use this page:</strong> Skim the section headers for the system involved, then match the clinical picture. If a patient is hot, rigid, and confused, the toxicology-and-hyperthermia section holds four look-alike syndromes that are treated completely differently &mdash; that kind of side-by-side is exactly what this hub is for. Bookmark this page; every new emergency guide gets added here.</p>
</div>

<h2>Shock, arrest and cardiovascular collapse</h2>
<p>The emergencies where minutes matter and the monitor speaks first. Obstructive shock has two great reversible causes &mdash; tamponade and tension pneumothorax &mdash; and both are diagnosed clinically, not by waiting for imaging. The malignant arrhythmias have their own logic: torsades is an electrolyte-and-QTc story, and Brugada-pattern VF hides in structurally normal hearts.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="septic-shock-nursing-guide-2026.html">Septic shock</a> &mdash; recognition, the hour-one bundle, pressors and reassessment</li>
<li><a href="cardiac-tamponade-icu-nurses-2026.html">Cardiac tamponade</a> &mdash; Beck's triad in real life and why fluids buy time</li>
<li><a href="tension-pneumothorax-icu-nurses-2026.html">Tension pneumothorax</a> &mdash; the clinical diagnosis you never image first</li>
<li><a href="torsades-de-pointes-icu-nurses-2026.html">Torsades de pointes</a> &mdash; magnesium first and the pacing/isoproterenol logic</li>
<li><a href="acquired-long-qt-qtc-monitoring-icu-nurses-2026.html">Acquired long QT &amp; QTc monitoring</a> &mdash; catching torsades before it happens</li>
<li><a href="brugada-syndrome-icu-nurses-2026.html">Brugada syndrome</a> &mdash; the ECG pattern that kills healthy hearts</li>
<li><a href="hypertensive-emergency-icu-nurses-2026.html">Hypertensive emergency</a> &mdash; controlled reduction, not normalization</li>
<li><a href="pulmonary-embolism-nursing-guide-2026.html">Pulmonary embolism</a> &mdash; risk-stratifying and the massive-PE decision tree</li>
</ul>

<h2>Endocrine and metabolic storms</h2>
<p>Endocrine emergencies are the great imitators &mdash; they arrive looking like sepsis, psychiatric illness, or simple dehydration. Each of these guides pairs a crisis with its mirror image: thyroid storm against myxedema coma, DKA against HHS. The electrolyte emergencies belong here too, because the correction rules are where patients get hurt a second time.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="thyroid-storm-icu-nurses-2026.html">Thyroid storm</a> &mdash; the block-then-wait drug order that must not be reversed</li>
<li><a href="myxedema-coma-icu-nurses-2026.html">Myxedema coma</a> &mdash; the hypothyroid crash and the steroid-before-levothyroxine rule</li>
<li><a href="adrenal-crisis-icu-nurses-2026.html">Adrenal crisis</a> &mdash; the shock that only steroids fix</li>
<li><a href="dka-vs-hhs-icu-nurses-2026.html">DKA vs HHS</a> &mdash; two hyperglycemic crises with different tempos and traps</li>
<li><a href="hyperkalemia-emergency-treatment-icu-nurses-2026.html">Hyperkalemia</a> &mdash; stabilize, shift, remove, in that order</li>
<li><a href="hyponatremia-correction-icu-nurses-2026.html">Hyponatremia correction</a> &mdash; the speed limits that prevent osmotic demyelination</li>
<li><a href="hypercalcemic-crisis-icu-nurses-2026.html">Hypercalcemic crisis</a> &mdash; fluids first, then the two-speed attack</li>
<li><a href="tumor-lysis-syndrome-icu-nurses-2026.html">Tumor lysis syndrome</a> &mdash; the oncologic emergency you can predict and prevent</li>
</ul>

<h2>Toxicology and the hyperthermia look-alikes</h2>
<p>Four syndromes present hot, rigid, and altered &mdash; malignant hyperthermia, neuroleptic malignant syndrome, serotonin syndrome, and thyroid storm &mdash; and the treatments do not overlap. Reading these guides together is the fastest way to build the differential. The overdose guides cover the poisonings where the antidote thinking is counterintuitive: hearts that need insulin, bradycardias that ignore atropine.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="malignant-hyperthermia-icu-nurses-2026.html">Malignant hyperthermia</a> &mdash; the anesthetic trigger and the dantrolene drill</li>
<li><a href="neuroleptic-malignant-syndrome-icu-nurses-2026.html">Neuroleptic malignant syndrome</a> &mdash; lead-pipe rigidity on a days-long clock</li>
<li><a href="serotonin-syndrome-icu-nurses-2026.html">Serotonin syndrome</a> &mdash; clonus, hyperreflexia, and the hours-long clock</li>
<li><a href="beta-blocker-overdose-icu-nurses-2026.html">Beta-blocker overdose</a> &mdash; glucagon, high-dose insulin, and bypassing the receptor</li>
<li><a href="digoxin-toxicity-icu-nurses-2026.html">Digoxin toxicity</a> &mdash; when potassium tells you how sick the heart is</li>
<li><a href="high-dose-insulin-euglycemia-hie-icu-nurses-2026.html">High-dose insulin euglycemic therapy</a> &mdash; the antidote that feels like a dosing error</li>
<li><a href="colchicine-toxicity-icu-nurses-2026.html">Colchicine toxicity</a> &mdash; the poison that kills in three acts</li>
<li><a href="baclofen-withdrawal-icu-nurses-2026.html">Baclofen withdrawal</a> &mdash; the pump emergency wearing a sepsis mask</li>
<li><a href="nerve-agent-poisoning-icu-nurses-2026.html">Nerve agents</a> &mdash; atropine to a dry chest, pralidoxime before aging</li>
<li><a href="vesicant-blister-agent-poisoning-icu-nurses-2026.html">Vesicant / blister agents</a> &mdash; mustard's painless delay vs lewisite's antidote</li>
</ul>

<h2>Obstetric emergencies</h2>
<p>OB crises land in adult ICUs whether or not the hospital has an obstetric service, and the physiology of pregnancy rewrites the normal rules &mdash; two patients, altered vital-sign baselines, and drug lists that change at delivery.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="preeclampsia-eclampsia-icu-nurses-2026.html">Preeclampsia &amp; eclampsia</a> &mdash; magnesium, blood pressure, and the delivery decision</li>
<li><a href="postpartum-hemorrhage-icu-nurses-2026.html">Postpartum hemorrhage</a> &mdash; the four Ts and the massive-transfusion trigger</li>
<li><a href="amniotic-fluid-embolism-icu-nurses-2026.html">Amniotic fluid embolism</a> &mdash; sudden collapse plus DIC at delivery</li>
<li><a href="peripartum-cardiomyopathy-icu-nurses-2026.html">Peripartum cardiomyopathy</a> &mdash; heart failure in the new mother</li>
</ul>

<h2>Burns, cold and environmental injury</h2>
<p>Thermal injury is a fluid-physiology problem first and a wound problem second. These guides run as a set: the resuscitation math, the airway that swells shut on a clock, the eschar that becomes a tourniquet, and injury made of ice.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="parkland-formula-burn-resuscitation-icu-nurses-2026.html">Parkland formula &amp; burn resuscitation</a> &mdash; titrate to urine output, not the formula</li>
<li><a href="smoke-inhalation-injury-icu-nurses-2026.html">Smoke inhalation</a> &mdash; three injuries on three clocks, CO and cyanide</li>
<li><a href="escharotomy-circumferential-burn-compartment-icu-nurses-2026.html">Escharotomy &amp; circumferential burns</a> &mdash; the tourniquet you can't see</li>
<li><a href="frostbite-cold-thermal-injury-icu-nurses-2026.html">Frostbite</a> &mdash; rapid rewarming, no-refreeze, and tPA limb salvage</li>
<li><a href="accidental-hypothermia-rewarming-icu-nurses-2026.html">Accidental hypothermia</a> &mdash; not dead until warm and dead</li>
</ul>

<h2>Neurologic crises</h2>
<p>Neuro emergencies are exam-driven: the monitor is your serial assessment, and deterioration is measured in subtle changes a scanner won't catch for hours. The neuromuscular pair &mdash; Guillain-Barr&eacute; and myasthenic crisis &mdash; share one bedside skill: catching respiratory failure before the blood gas does.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="status-epilepticus-icu-nurses-2026.html">Status epilepticus</a> &mdash; benzodiazepines first, and the timed escalation ladder</li>
<li><a href="subarachnoid-hemorrhage-vasospasm-icu-nurses-2026.html">Subarachnoid hemorrhage &amp; vasospasm</a> &mdash; the day-4-to-14 watch</li>
<li><a href="guillain-barre-syndrome-icu-nurses-2026.html">Guillain-Barr&eacute; syndrome</a> &mdash; ascending weakness and the vital-capacity trigger</li>
<li><a href="myasthenic-crisis-icu-nurses-2026.html">Myasthenic crisis</a> &mdash; weakness that fails the airway, and the cholinergic mimic</li>
<li><a href="wernicke-encephalopathy-icu-nurses-2026.html">Wernicke encephalopathy</a> &mdash; thiamine before glucose, every time</li>
</ul>

